<p>President Trump said he has ordered the Pentagon to begin planning for potential military action in Nigeria after accusing the country of allowing Islamist militants to carry out a “mass slaughter” of Christians, and he warned he could cut off U.S. aid if the government does not act . The White House also re-designated Nigeria as a country of particular concern for religious freedom, escalating diplomatic pressure while the Nigerian government disputes the allegations and says it remains committed to religious freedom . The move marks a significant escalation in rhetoric between Washington and Abuja and could affect security cooperation and assistance depending on next steps .</p><img src='https://kagiproxy.com/img/xO7tkGSGPAysU0WLlDVlXQenGeMjoYietUCpbn6amzuViQvkyh8wqBLhl3Vgloa_EQwyDZza_1QNwmKzAYwiyvt0qlTuLYc_cbbJy9tE0bEFBB6G5I_ZezadkTqP9eYFENzTA-Wtda5NES3WmMnQ7sn8hnamIY2Q9Gb4gArmPHNsksb2Wjf5B9jN1CMhWi6n4u7X892uPeA' alt='President Trump in Palm Beach, Fla., on Friday.' /><br /><h3>Highlights:</h3><ul><li>Religious designation: The administration re-added Nigeria to a U.S. watch list as a “country of particular concern” over religious freedom, a step that can precede sanctions or restrictions .</li><li>Domestic politics: U.S. conservative lawmakers and commentators pressed for action, and senators including Ted Cruz had urged formal designation over allegations of &quot;Christian mass murder&quot; before the president&#x27;s announcement .</li><li>Rhetorical escalation: Mr. Trump used combative language on social media describing possible troop action and vowed to ‘wipe out’ Islamist fighters, language that has intensified the diplomatic dispute .</li><li>Nigerian response: President Bola Tinubu and Nigerian officials rejected the president’s characterization and reiterated Nigeria’s official commitment to religious freedom amid the dispute .</li></ul><blockquote>If the Nigerian Government continues to allow the killing of Christians, the U.S.A. will immediately stop all aid and assistance to Nigeria, and may very well go into that now disgraced country, ‘guns-a-blazing,’ to completely wipe out the Islamic Terrorists who are committing these horrible atrocities. - President Donald Trump</blockquote><h3>Perspectives:</h3><ul><li>President Trump / White House: The president said he ordered the Pentagon to plan for potential military action and accused Nigeria of failing to stop killings of Christians, warning of aid suspension if the government does not act . (<a href='https://www.npr.org/2025/11/01/g-s1-96215/trump-nigeria-christian-persecution-claims'>NPR</a>)</li><li>President Bola Tinubu / Nigerian government: Nigeria’s president and officials rejected the accusations, saying the government remains committed to religious freedom and disputing claims that it is permitting mass killings . (<a href='https://www.firstpost.com/world/tinubu-rejects-trumps-claim-of-christian-persecution-says-nigeria-remains-committed-to-religious-freedom-ws-e-13947050.html'>Firstpost</a>)</li></ul><h3>Sources:</h3><ul><li><a href='https://www.france24.com/en/africa/20251102-trump-threatens-to-send-us-military-into-nigeria-alleging-mass-killing-of-christians'>Trump threatens to send US military into Nigeria, alleging mass killing of Christians</a> - france24.com</li><li><a href='https://www.ft.com/content/d0c7c8e8-a7d4-48a6-b263-5006a2632159'>Trump threatens Nigeria with military action over violence against Christians</a> - ft.com</li><li><a href='https://www.npr.org/2025/11/01/g-s1-96215/trump-nigeria-christian-persecution-claims'>Trump threatens military action in Nigeria over Christian persecution claims</a> - npr.org</li><li><a href='https://www.politico.com/news/2025/11/01/trump-us-military-nigeria-00632716'>Trump threatens to deploy the military ‘guns-a-blazing’ to Nigeria</a> - politico.com</li><li><a href='https://www.dw.com/en/nigeria-flaunts-religious-freedoms-after-trump-designation/a-74587490'>Nigeria flaunts religious freedoms after 